------------------------------------------------------------------------------


   This is the page where I want to tell you more about myself.

   So, my mother decided that my name should be Heiko Schröder. And this is still my name.
   Since I was born I live in the city of Leipzig which is well known for its fair.
   Many of you may want to know how old I am. Well, it is no secret. I'm 26 years old now.

   Since 07-05-97 I'm a graduated engineer in telecommunications with a
   specialization in »Technical Writing and Communications«.
   Also called  »Technical Documentation«.
   The topic of my final exam was named:
   Writing a manual for the time documentation system »leancom 4.0 for Windows«.
   (Unfortunately nothing for our Amiga ;-( )

   By the way, my university the »Fachhochschule Leipzig der Deutschen Telekom AG« was
   the first university in Germany offering such a special study.
   Translated into understandable words it means that have to work on
   documentations for devices, advertisements, multimedia, layout, printing, DTP,
   interface design and so on.
   I think everybody knows the "perfect" manuals that nobody understands even 
   the writer itself doesn't. Now I'm on the way changing this situation with easy to understand
   and useful manuals. I'm self-employed and create manuals for other companies - maybe for you
   too if you want!

                           docu:media
                  Peter Teich & Heiko Schröder GbR
              Ingenieurbüro für Technische Dokumentation

              Kommandant-Prendel-Allee 89
              D-04299 Leipzig

              Tel.: +49 (0) 3 41 - 86 22 33 1
              Fax : +49 (0) 3 41 - 86 22 38 3

   The AMIGA is used in my company too.
   Therefor most the time I use FinalWriter for creating texts of a documentation.
   But I noticed that all the Windows-PC programs offer a lot more possibilities
   to make work more comfortable. Even if they have a higher demand for up to date
   hardware (memory and HD space).

   Because of that I'm writing help programs (ARexx macros) which make
   working with FW more easy and comfortable.
   Some macros are available at Aminet (without graphical user interface):
@{fg shine}      biz/swood/FW_Font.lha
      biz/swood/FW_GfxClip.lha
      biz/swood/FW_MEf.lha
      biz/swood/FW_SaveLoad.lha
      biz/swood/FW_Templates.lha
@{fg text}
   Likewise I have created all the macros with a GUI for interested
   FinalWriter users.
   An overview, screenshots and descriptions about the existing
   macros can be obtained there:
@{fg shine}      biz/swood/FW_AllInOne.lha
@{fg text}
   I distribute this package with the GUI macros and some bonus macros by payment.
   The bonus macros are not available at Aminet in any way.

@{fg fill}Attention! I'm ready!@{fg text}
   The macro package is finally ready. It has taken a damn long time, that's true.
   But I got help of a very excellent and competent beta tester.
   Andy, thank you very much for all the time you have used for testing
   the macros thoroughly and sending me detailed reports.
   I haven't count all the emails... ;-)

   Note: The macros are only available in German language. An English version is
   planned but it's not sure when they will be finish. 
   The macro package V3 includes the following macros:

   AmigaGuide-Import  - V1.0 - Imports AmigaGiude as formatted text
   Compress           - V3.0 - Compressing FW-files while saving and open them
   Datenbank-Import   - V1.0 - Import databases as tables (needs FW 5)
   Fenster            - V1.1 - Quick arrange of open documents
   FontCode           - V3.0 - Type exotic characters
   FontLook           - V4.1 - Type of font manager, easy view/print of all your fonts
   FootnoteManagement - V1.0 - Finally footnotes for FW!!! (needs FW 97)
   GuideLines         - V1.1 - Setting up guide lines exactly (needs FW 97)
   Layouter           - V1.1 - Change page orientation and format correctly
   MultiplePaste      - V3.0 - Copy objects exactly and multiple times
   MoreTextBlock      - V2.1 - More than 35 characters per text block
   Objekte ausrichten - V3.0 - Align objects
   ObjektManager      - V1.0 - Overview about all objects in a FW document
   Spaltenbreite      - V1.0 - Change the column width of a table (needs FW 5)
   Suchen & Ersetzen  - V2.1 - Special Search/Replace function
   TabellenSchrift    - V1.0 - Change easy layout of cells (needs FW 5)
   VerweisAssistent   - V1.0 - ?? automatisch Verweise setzen und aktualisieren??
   Vorschau           - V1.1 - Print preview at the monitor

   More information and screenshots at Aminet:
               @{fg shine}biz/swood/FW_AllInOne.lha@{fg text}

   BTW: Visit the FinalWriter page on my Homebase @{fg fill}»http://yi.com/home/SchroederHeiko«@{fg text}
 
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Leipzig, 02-22-98                                           Heiko Schröder

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mailing" "The first FinalWriter mailing list!"


   Planed for a long time it is now reality - the first mailing list only about FW.
   Because there are a lot of offers for free mailing lists on I have dicided to
   create a list at http://www.coollist.com on 02-16-98.
   This list is for beginners as well as for experts in FinalWriter.

   The subscription of the @{fg shine}1st FinalWriter mailing list@{fg text}
   can be done at my FinalWriter web page (Attention: case sensitive server!):

         http://www.yi.com/home/SchroederHeiko/FinalWriter-eng.html

   At the page you can put in your email address and press the subscribe button.
   Something later you get an email by Coollist as a confirmation.
   You reply this email unchanged to the sender and you are finally subscribed.
   Now you can join the exchange in experiences and tricks.
   If the subscription via the web page doesn't work at all please send an email
   to me (@{fg shine}age@thepentagon.com@{fg text}) with the wish to subscribe. I will then put you
   in the list.

   After all the email address of the list is @{fg shine}finalwriter@coollist.com@{fg text}.
   Unfortunately the mailing service isn't very comfortable. For example
   it is not possible for you to gather information on how many users are
   subscribed and so on.

   Only I as the admin of the list can do this. But if you wish to know some statistic
   information of the list I will make them public onto my web site. No problem ;-)
   There are also plans to collect the emails and publish them monthly at Aminet.

   For all the people out there who don't know what a mailing list is here comes
   a little introduction. Experts may continue browsing the guide.

 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

   A little introduction to the mailing list:

   After subscribing the list it starts.
   If anybody writes an email to finalwriter@coollist.com it is
   automatically distributed to everybody subscribed to the list.

   Now you have the possibility to answer this email. This is done by simply
   reply to the email. Please make sure that the receiver is finalwriter@coollist.com.
   Also your answer will now be distributed to everybody in the list.
   You will receive your email too (you then know everything works correctly).

   But sure you don't need to reply to every email. ;-) If you like to, you
   can only read the incoming emails.

   It is that simple. Nothing more to say about it.

   But hold on:
   Please don't bother the list with huge attachments. And take note of
   the netiquette.

   I hope you have fun using this list and hopefully the list will help
   you getting out more of FinalWriter without getting into trouble.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch01" "Suggestions by Jörg-W. Lehner - 01-18-97"

   @{fg shine}Better handling of subscript and superscript characters:@{fg text}

      Subscript and superscript characters are ignored when converting in
      graphics (important for labels on graphics).

      If there are some text attributes to change but they are on different
      positions it would be useful to have the possibility of a sort of multiple
      selection (Mouse+Shift key).

      A similar problem are Greek characters in texts with Latin letters
      (angle "alpha"=30°, R=20kOhm).

      In this situation it would be desirable to have a possibility for fixing
      fonts for not changing them by mistake. It happens again and again that
      you change kOhm into kW by mistake when changing the font for a paragraph.
      A disastrous exchange.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch02" "Suggestion by Christian Beck - 01-21-97"

   @{fg shine}Linebreak@{fg text}

      How can you insert a line break (no new paragraph) manually (or by
      macro)?

@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch03" "Suggestions by Hans Schörner - 02-15-97"

   @{fg shine}Different numbers of columns on one page@{fg text}

      Normally I get this problem if I use text in more than one column
      and a headline that is larger than one single column.
      To do this I need to select one column for the headline and
      for instance 2 or 3 columns for the text.
      I want to avoid to use a lot of frames because that is not the
      purpose and meaning of them.

   @{fg shine}Supplement:@{fg text}
      With FW97 you can use the text frame function to avoid this
      problem.
               Heiko

   @{fg shine}Determine where to hyphenate/divide words@{fg text}

      Some words are not hyphenated correctly. So it is useful to determine
      by yourself where to make a hyphenation. Some programs like "Beckertext"
      use the combination "CTRL" + "-" to insert a soft hyphen that does this.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch04" "Suggestions by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr. 1, D-04299 Leipzig - 03-18-97"

   @{fg shine}Tables@{fg text}

      What about joining or splitting cells of tables?

   @{fg shine}import/export@{fg text}

      I'm desperately missing a reasonable import/export filter.
      Who is working with WordPerfect, PenPal or ProWrite?
      In my opinion a export/import filter for MS WinWord would be
      quite useful.
      Saving in the RTF format is one solution but it isn't perfect.
      If the text includes graphics the system fails totally.
      As the name says: rich TEXT format.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "wunsch06" "1st Email from Achim Klopsch to Softwood"

>I am using FW5.05 and I have some problems with printouts. FW runs on an
>own screen (800x600, 16 colors) Often the printout stops and the mouse is
>frozen.
>This happens mainly with 720x720 prints.
>
>On multiscan productivity the whole FW- screen vanished. Only a black
>screen is shown by window-demon.
>
>I had some e-mail contacts to other users, which also have printing problems.
>
>During printing the colors of the cybergrfx FW screen often change. There
>is still a display problem.
>
>Did you improve stability in FW97? Especially with gfx-cards?
>I would be glad to hear from you.

@{fg shine}Die Antwort von Softwood@{fg text}
To my knowledge, nothing was changed as regards Final Writer's behavior on
graphics cards.

Some testing has been done on allowing Final Writer to acquire memory in a
different manner for the printing process, but the testing was too
preliminary for us to feel comfortable adding the new method to Final
Writer 97.


--
- Ric Fischer (http://www.softwood.com/users/ric)
- SoftWood, Inc. (http://www.softwood.com)
- Disclaimer:  The views and opinions expressed here are my own.
  They are not necessarily shared by SoftWood, Inc.
- Quote (from Robert Browning):
  "Ah, but a man's reach should exceed his grasp, or what's a heaven for?"


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch07" "2nd Email from Achim Klopsch to Softwood"

>I am forced to use a pc in the office and I use FW at home. Therefore I need
>full
>conversion facilities between winword and FW. At the moment RTF is limited
>to basic functions only. E.g. there is no support for graphical elements
>like lines.
>When I make a RTF export/import directly in winword it works fine. There
>must be functions which are not supported by FW jet.
>
>I think there are a lot of people in the same situation. (Bloody pc in the
>office...) An improvement would increase the acceptance of FW and the AMIGA
>too.
>
>I look forward to your answer.

@{fg shine}Die Antwort von Softwood@{fg text}
If enough users request a particular new feature, it will usually be added
to the next version.


--
- Ric Fischer (http://www.softwood.com/users/ric)
- SoftWood, Inc. (http://www.softwood.com)
- Disclaimer:  The views and opinions expressed here are my own.
  They are not necessarily shared by SoftWood, Inc.
- Quote (from Robert Browning):
  "Ah, but a man's reach should exceed his grasp, or what's a heaven for?"

@{fg shine}My opinion:@{fg text}
All FW users should point Softwood out to the importance of this function as it
is necessary to stay compatible with other programs.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch11" "Wishes by Markus Steblei - 06-28-97"

   @{fg shine}Printing@{fg text}
      Printing out of FAST-RAM not the slow Chip-RAM. The time of waiting
      while printing is sometimes really not acceptable anymore.
      Although I'm using Turboprint 5.02 my HP850C needs 1,5 minutes for a standard
      A4 page out of FW (s/w, text only)!
      Also sending a fax out of FW (using MultiFax) is torment slow, 2 minutes
      are really fast in this situation (also with a 68060 and Picasso IV)...


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch12" "Wishes by Karl-Heinz Ostertag - 06-20-97"

   1. When opening a file, MS Word offers the possibility to choose from the
   	last x documents (e.g. 5) that have been used.
	   I would like to have this feature in FinalWriter too because I often
   	use documents more than once. To go through all the files at every time
	   is arduous.

   2. Tables. If you are pressing the TAB key in the last cell of the last row
      in a table in MS Word a new row is inserted automatically.
      This feature would be quite nice for FinalWriter too, right?

   Others:
   On a 68040 FinalWriter runs actually quite fast (compared with my former
	68000 processor).
	With a postscript laser printer the speed of the printing process is very
	fast.	Actually I'm completely satisfied with FinalWriter.

      With friendly greetings

      K.H Ostertag <;-><

@{fg shine}Solution for 1.):@{fg text}

There's a macro buzzing around in Aminet bypassing this problem. ;-)
Aminet: util/rexx/RecentDocs.lha (by Ron Goertz)



@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch13" "Wishes by Karl-Heinz Freese - 07-13-97"

	   In my opinion FinalWriter is the best word processing
	   for the Amiga.
	   Improvements I want:
		With pressing a key the cursor should jump directly to:
		a) end of a line,
		b) first position of a line.

@{fg shine}Solution by Heiko Schröder:@{fg text}

      It's not just pressing a single key like on a PC but it is
	   possible the following way:

         Ctrl + Alt + Cursor right  = end of line
         Ctrl + Alt + Cursor links  = start of line

	   You can found more shortcuts for moving through documents
	   @{"here" link "frage026"}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch16" "Wish by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr. 1, D-04299 Leipzig - 08-12-97"

   @{fg shine}RTF export with FW97@{fg text}

   Attention! If you want to put a document to another computer system
	(e.g. PC Windows) with the help of the RTF format, you should NOT use
	the text frame function.
	Otherwise you will be angry about a time intensive conversion into the
   text mode.
   Because the content of a text frame won't be exported into the RTF format.
   (see graphics).


   @{fg shine}Text frames@{fg text}

   You should be careful with the spell checking tool too if you use text
	frames. The spell checking only works in text mode or in the current
	text frame (where the cursor is situated).
 	All the other frames are ignored.

	This should be corrected by Softwood as soon as possible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch17" "Wish by Andreas Block - 08-18-97"


	It would be desirable in any case to have a @{" formula editor" link "frage022"} in FW
	and to have the possibility to insert hard spaces (they belong to a word
	and can not be separated).

   @{fg shine}Solution by Adolf Markus Berthold - 12-02-97"@{fg text}

   Have you ever tried pressing @{fg fill}<alt>-<SPACE>@{fg text}?

   Unfortunately hard spaces are optical not different compared to
   the normal ones.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch18" "Wishes by Manni Froitzheim - 08-02-97"

Recently I've downloaded the latest version of you FW Tips`N`Tricks
out of the Aminet and now I want to give my opinion to some things.

   At first I think it's very kind of you to always have the Tips`n`tricks
   up to date and therefore creating a forum for the FW/FC users.

   1. Footnotes are still missing

   2. Why can't fonts be shown in a separate window (like in WordWorth)
      for directly getting an idea how the font look like.

   3. I miss built in functions to add special effects to text.
      Note by @{"H.S." link "Age"}: Special effects can be created with FinalWrapper
      (to be found in Aminet)

   4. Import/export filters for all the other common word processing programs,
      like WordWorth, for MS-DOS and Apple computers.

   5. Marking a list not only with dots but also to have a numbered version.

   6. There's no possibility for creating my own graphics for the user menu
      bar
      (see also @{"here" link "frage030"})

   7. It would be nice to support HTML tags for creating own pages directly.

Well, that are almost all my wishes.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "wunsch19" "Wish by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr. 1, D-04299 Leipzig - 10-13-97"

   @{fg shine}Multiple UNDO@{fg text}
   	It isn't enough for me that you can use the UNDO function only once.
      A professional word processing and DTP program should offer a more
      sophisticated function.
      But I think I'm not the only user demanding this ;-)


@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage01" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   While loading a Windows postscript font into FW/FC always an eternity is
   passing by (up to 1 minute on a standard Amiga 500). Maybe there's a way
   to do this more elegant?


@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   Before you try to convert please read @{"this" link "frage033"}.

   Conversion of postscript fonts into the Intellifont format (OS2.0 or greater).

   You need the program @{b}»TypeSmith v2.5c Aminet«@{ub}. Full version is available
   at the CD Aminet 10 (February 96).
   You also need the program @{b}»MvPSF«@{ub}. This one can be found on the CD Aminet 12
   (June 96) or directly at Aminet (text/font/MVPSF.lha). It gives back the real name
   To the font.

   1. Create new directories/drawers in the FWFonts directory/drawer.
      e.g.: FWFonts
              ------- SWOLFonts
                        ------- name of directory
                                  ------- _bullet_outlines

   2. Use @{b}"MvPSF"@{ub} (MvPSF [old .pfb-font directory name] all stat)
                                    or
@{fg shine}NEW@{fg text}   @{b}RenamePS2FW@{ub} (Aminet-biz/swood/) - renames all the Fonts to the special
      FinalWriter format (_bold, _italic, _bolditalic and so on)

   3. Start @{b}"Typesmith v2.5c Aminet"@{ub}
      * import of the .pfb fonts
      * export to Intellifonts into the _bullet_outline directory

   4. Start the program @{b}"Intellifont"@{ub} (system directory)
      * at the left side (Outline Font Source) select the
        _bullet_outline directory
      * at the right side (Destination Font Drawer) there's automatically
        displayed the font directory

      * select the fonts you want to install on the left side
      * Press "Install Marked Typefaces"

   5. Start a program for editing files (e.g. @{b}»DOpus«@{ub})
      * copy (or better move) all the files with the extention (.font, .otag)
        out of the Fonts: directory into the fonts subdirectory of the FW drawer
        (don't copy/move them into the _bullet_outlines directory!)
      * copy (once again: better move) all the files ending with .type out of
        Fonts: bullet_outlines directory into the Fonts/bullet_outlines/
        subdirectory of the FW directory
      * Rename the files in the _bullet_outlines directory
        e.g.   source                                target

   @{fg fill}                  font                                    font
               ---_bullet_outlines                    ---_bullet_outlines@{fg text}
                  AltSchwab_D.type                       AlteSchwabacherD.type
                  FetFrak_D.type                         FetteFrakturD.type

               AlteSchwabacherD.font                  AlteSchwabacherD.font
               AlteSchwabacherD.otag                  AlteSchwabacherD.otag
               FetteFrakturD.font                     FetteFrakturD.font
               FetteFrakturD.otag                     FetteFrakturD.otag

   5. Start @{b}»Finalwriter«@{ub} or @{b}»FinalCopyII«@{ub}
      * use the font with the extension .font

   That's all.
   No eternal waiting when using .pfb font files.
   Besides of that you can use Truetype fonts (.ttf) the same way.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   An Amiga needs some time when reading .pfb files because it takes some time
   to convert the data into an Amiga usable format.
   And this procedure may last a very long time.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage02" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   When starting there are a number of fonts to use but there's not enough memory
   for printing afterwards. However, the fonts can't be deleted also if they are
   not necessary anymore.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   Open the menu "Layout - Fonts...". Select the font "Softsans".
   Mark "As standard" and save with "OK". Terminate @{b}»Finalwriter«@{ub} and
   start it again. From now on there's only Softsans available ant printing
   should work without any problem.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   The normal standard font is Softsans. If you select another font as standard
   Softsans isn't replaced but the other font is added.
   This only takes unnecessary memory when you don't use it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage03" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   For me, printing out of Finalwriter/-CopyII lasts much to long.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   The use of a spooler or print manger puts things right.
   Don't be afraid that isn't a hardware solution it's a software.
   These programs (spooler) catch the data on its way to the printer.
   Therefor the original program (e.g. FW) "thinks" that the data has
   been processed fast by the printer and sends out the next data. 
   And so the time for printing one page reduces from maybe 3 minutes 
   down to a half or 1 minute.
   With a document of 40 pages this sums up to a lot time saved.
   While the printer still does its job you can now carry on working on
   your document.
   The program @{b}PrintManager 2.0@{ub} by Nicola Salmoria does a good job
   for this. It's available at Aminet:text/print/Printmanager_2.0.lha  and
   Time 212, Saar 612 or 742.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   Normally the printer gets the prepared data to print it. In many cases 
   this can take some time. Especially on printers with a small buffer
   memory (dot printer: 16 KB).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage04" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   How do I prepare a file (to export it ready for printing) if I want to
   let it print out by a professional print company.
   As you probably know they don't use Amiga and FinalWriter.

@{fg shine}Solution No. 1:@{fg text}
   If the repro company uses PC and Win95 you can acquire the Windows version
   of FinalWriter 5.05. But mostly they work with Macintosh computers.
   And by the way, how gives money for a Windows version anyway?-)

@{fg shine}Solution No. 2:@{fg text}
   The more elegant and cheaper way is to print out the document in the
   Adobe PostScript 2.0 format. You need at least OS 2.0 for this.

   Attention:
   When creating the document you  should use an Adobe PS font (.pfb)
   because otherwise there may be problems with the printing.

   Menu: Project | Print...
   Adjust:
      Print process = PostScript file

   Press button PostScript... for changing the configuration.
   The common configuration:
      Printer type   = parallel
      Color          = Color
      Font download  = 1x per font
      Page format    = actual document size
   Leave with "Okay".

   Now select what to print and send it off.
   Choose a file name! With .ps at the end.
   Okay for now.

   Now create a PC disk using the device PC0: or PC1: in the system
   drawer Storage/DOSDrivers/ (formatting) .
   Because the saved .ps file is a text file you have to activate
   CrossDOS.
   Configuration: PC0: or PC1:
                  Activate text filter
                  Text conversion inactive
                  Type of conversion: ASCII-7

   You can copy now the .ps file onto the PC disc to take it with you for
   the print.

   By the way: FinalWriter writes the information of the .pfb font into
               the .ps file. So this font is not necessary at the "print" PC.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage05" "Question Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, 04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   If I change the page size DIN A4 (210*297) into DIN A3 (297*420) right
   after the start of FinalWriter I can not scroll the whole width of the
   DIN A3 page with the scroll bar at the bottom.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   Menu: View | Zoom | 25%
   After doing this switch to the 100% view of the page again.
   Menu: View | Zoom | 100%
   Now it is possible to scroll over the whole widt.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
    Another bug to take care of by Softwood. :-(

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage06" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   Actually this is not a problem. I found this while playing around and trying
   everything!

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   What about some keyboard short cuts?

   Quick magnification:
      Hold down Alt key and press mouse button.
      Zoom to 50 | 100 | 200 | 400%

   Quick reducing zoom:
      Hold down Shift, right Alt key and press mouse button
      Zoom to 200 | 100 | 50 | 25%

   Moving in the document:
      Hold down right Amiga key and press mouse button.
      Now move the mouse. Everything okay?

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   These functions are not described in the manual.

   Do you know some more? Come on and tell me... ;-)

@ENDNODE


@NODE "frage07" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

   Public screen of FinalWriter

      From FinalWriter 5 on Arexx programmers are offered the possibility
      to open the window on the FW PubScreen.

               PublicScreen="FinalWriterPubScreen"

      Therefor it's no longer necessary to open windows on the Workbench.
      This means no manually switching (Right-Amiga N) by the users any longer.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage08" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   How would it be to change font attributes/styles (normal, bold, italic,
   underlined) on the fly while typing without even touching the mouse?
   Many programs support this by Ctrl-N, Ctrl-B, Ctrl-S, Ctrl-I.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   It's not that easy unfortunately. But you can realize this with the help
   of the user preferences and 5 minutes of time.

   Menu @{b}User|Others|Preferences...@{ub}

   Set up the following:

   name of the selection | type  | command or name      | function shortcut
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   standard/normal       | macro | STYLE Normal         | e.g.:  Ctrl F1
   bold                  | macro | STYLE Bold           |        Ctrl F2
   italic                | macro | STYLE Italic         |        Ctrl F3
   underlined            | macro | STYLE Underline      |        Ctrl F4

   "Accept" and "Save" everything.
   (For more information on how to use the preferences read your manual.)

   Now you can use the selected shortcuts to change the various styles while
   you type the text.


@{fg shine}Attention:@{fg text}
   With this there are no limits for setting up more shortcuts.
   But think of the fact that one time all keys are used. Just try.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage09" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   The display of the document on the screen isn't comparable with
   the printout. The proportion of height and width isn't correct at all!

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   To display a view of the print out with the correct proportion of the
   sides do the following:

   Get the proportion of the visible part of the screen.
   e.g.: VWidth=270mm; VHeight=200mm
         VProportion = VWidth/VHeight = 270mm/200mm = 1.35

   Get the proportion of the screen resolution.
         RWidth=1280 Pixel; RHeight=512 Pixel   (SuperHighres Interlace)
         RProportion = RWidth/RHeight/2 = 1280/512/2    = 1.25

   Now you have to move to the Menu: View | Options... -> Display.
   The proportion of the horizontal and vertical display (DPI) has to be
   the same with the proportion of the monitor.
   e.g.: horizontal = 152 DPI
         Vertical   = horizontal/VProportion/RProportion
                    = 152 DPI / 1.35 / 1.25
                    =  90 DPI

   Don't forget to save!

   Now finally the display is the same with the printout.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage010" "Question by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   My father-in-law owns an A500 with 2.3MB memory.
   He works with EPS graphics and often he gets an out of memory message
   If he tries to print the document. 
   He also think that it is quite terrible that documents including graphics
   are getting often bigger than 1MB very fast.

@{fg shine}Solution No. 1:@{fg text}
   Memory shortage:
   Double click a graphic. In the "Graphics Properties" window check 
   "Cross frame". Now set this as default. And leave the window.
   Now all embedded graphics are displayed with a cross frame. 
   To purge the memory that was already used save the document, close it and
   open it again. 
   Look! The memory is free but the document still contains the graphics!
   Little side effect: Working is getting faster because FW doesn't need to
   reload the graphics.

@{fg shine}Solution No. 2:@{fg text}
   Size of the file:
   Double click a graphic.
   In the preferences window change the @{b}Option Save/Link@{ub}
   to "Save link". Leave the window with @{b}Use@{ub}.
   Now not the linked graphics are saved but only the path where to find
   the file. This saves you incredible much space on your HD or disc.
   ATTENTION: You have to repeat this procedure for every single graphics.

   STOP: If you want to share documents with other users you have to save
         the graphics files because the path to the file won't be the same 
         on the other machine most the cases.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   Normally FinalWriter loads all the graphics into memory
   and saves them into the document too.
   This means double the waste of free space.
   When using the cross frame view only a placebo is visible that 
   stands for graphics.
   Only for printing purposes the graphics data is loaded one by one into memory
   and immediately purged. 
   This saves RAM space and time.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage011" "Tip by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   It is possible to set rules to measure in either "Inches", "Metric"
   or "Picas". Does this make sense for me and how do I convert them 
   from one to another?

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   The graphics and DTP business uses "Picas" (the Pica point).
   Font size is often measured this way.
   But step by step:
   The Pica point (pt) @{fg text} =  0.353 mm = 1/72 Inch
      @{fg shine}1 Inch@{fg text} = 25.4   mm =   72 pt


   This is a conversion table:

                        mm |   pt       mm |   pt
                       ------------    ------------
                         1 |  2.835     11 | 31.181
                         2 |  5.669     12 | 34.016
                         3 |  8.504     13 | 36.850
                         4 | 11.339     14 | 39.685
                         5 | 14.173     15 | 42.520
                         6 | 17.008     16 | 45.354
                         7 | 19.843     17 | 48.189
                         8 | 22.677     18 | 51.024
                         9 | 25.512     19 | 53.858
                        10 | 28.346     20 | 56.693

                        pt |   mm       pt |   mm
                       ------------    ------------
                         1 |  0.353     11 |  3.881
                         2 |  0.706     12 |  4.233
                         3 |  1.058     13 |  4.586
                         4 |  1.411     14 |  4.939
                         5 |  1.764     15 |  5.292
                         6 |  2.117     16 |  5.644
                         7 |  2.469     17 |  5.997
                         8 |  2.822     18 |  6.350
                         9 |  3.175     19 |  6.703
                        10 |  3.528     20 |  7.056



@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage012" "Tip by Heiko Schröder, Arnoldstr.1, D-04299 Leipzig"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   How do I change line spacing? Only "Single", "1 1/2" and "Double" does not
   fill my needs. And what does "Variable" means?

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   "Single", "1 1/2" and "Double" are fixed line spaces according to the point
   size of the font.
   By using "Variable" you can set up line spacing individually.
   But the question is how do I do this? Easy as this:
   Select your text and set the line spacing to "Variable".
   Now open @{b}Layout | Font spec...@{ub} (FW5+).
   Select the line spacing you want using @{fg fill}Spacing@{fg text}.
   (Attention: Make sure that at the right hand side the box "Spacing" is not
   selected!!) 

   Now you have got your special individual spacing.

   To be typographically correct notice this:
      line spacing = font size + 1-2 pt
   If the spacing is smaller than the font size, the text lines may interfere.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   In my opinion this function is never described. They only pointed out
   that it is available. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage013" "Question by Siegfried Sulovsky"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   ... It is also annoying that if you create a new section (main as standard)
   you manually have to copy headers and footers from the previous section.
   The "Easy Header/Footer..." function of the tool menu unfortunately changes
   the format of the page. And graphics must be inserted by hand anyway.
   It should be possible to create a template that optionally can be used with all pages of
   a document.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   At least there is a script that saves graphics of a page as a template...
   You should be able to find the macro "GfxClip" in the "FWMacros" drawer. 
   You can find it definitely on the FW original disks.   
   This macro searches all selected graphics and writes a macro containig
   all the data of the graphics.
   All you have to do is to start this macro and after that the graphics
   automatically appear on the page currently viewed. No matter what section.

   Unfortunately this macro's date is 09-21-94 and because of that it doesn't
   know the latest features of FinalWriter (text frames, tables and so on).
   Besides of that it don't handles right positions.

   Heiko (that's me) and Arndt Bußmann, both have individually revised the original.
   We will join all our improvements and changes to one new macro that will be
   available at Aminet:
                         "biz/swood/FW_GfxClip.lha"

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   Softwood has probably realized the problem and therefor programmed this 
   "insignificant" macro but they forgot to developed according to the new
   functions.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage014" "Question by Siegfried Sulovsky"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   I have the following problem. If I type large texts, I always divide the 
   document into several sections. After I have finished a section I often
   add new sentences and paragraphs because of for instance mistakes. 
   Now the section is getting bigger and bigger.
   In the next sections the page numbers will not be increased automatically.
   This is really getting on my nerves if you have 14 sections and you will 
   add something important to the first section.

   Besides of that I miss something of an update function for the Table of
   Contents. Maybe somebody can write a macro?

@{fg shine}Solution for the page numbes by Siegfried himself:@{fg text}
   At sometime I stupidly changed the settings in the dialog Layout|Section...|Pages
   for "Numbered by" from "Document" to "Section" and then saved the document.

   Note by the editor:
   So you have to check "Document".


@{fg shine}Solution for the Table of Content problem:@{fg text}
   You don't need a macro for this but it also don't work by itself.
   You have to format the headlines with a paragraph style that generates
   a Table of Content entry (look at your manual). 
   After that choose "Section|Create..." and the "Table of Contents".
   When changing a headline use the same procedure again and the TOC
   is updated automatically.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage015" "Question by Arndt Bußmann"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   The problems started in March 97. At this time I replaced my PicassoII 
   and CyberGFX with PicassoIV and Picasso96. Exactly 2 days before my
   presentation (never change a running system, you know).
   Everything was okay until I tried to print pages that contain small images
   using FW5 and Turboprint 5.0 (I need it to use the HP870, otherwise it 
   wouldn't print).
   The result was a printout on which all the graphics (also simple circles
   and boxes) are covered with a horizontal stripe that changes the color
   information with something like a XOR function.
   The printouts are simply not acceptable.
   Also with FW97 and Picasso96_1_20 there was no change.
   I would like to know if there are some others that know this problem too.

@{fg shine}Solution by Michael Krüger - 12-02-97:@{fg text}
   I noticed the error described (printing out of FW generates a thick color stripe,
   the other pictures look like changed by a XOR-function) first after I
   installed "Executive".
   The author of this task scheduler pointed out in his manual that FW has 
   a bug in its use of the printer.device:
   FW needs the priority of the printer.device to be set to 0. 
   For the normal usage it is zero that's true, but no Commodore/AT guideline has 
   ever demanded this. So it is quite legit to change the priority of a
   device. But FW doesn't like this at all. 
   "Executive" therefor gives the advice to exclude printer.device from the
   explicit scheduling. 
   For me, this was only sometimes a successful because again and again there
   was this graphic error explained above, especially with large documents.

   It's amazing that this error also has something to do with TurboPrint 5.0:
   I noticed that there error only occurs if I deactivate "Use pure Black" 
   in the "Graphics" part of the dithering options.
   Once again: Switch on "Pure Black" and there error is gone. But for this
   soft color shading gets lost.
   If I need them I have to terminate "Executive" for the moment and everything
   works as usual.


@{fg shine}Solution by Letter from Udo Rahn - 10-11-97:@{fg text}
   Graphical color printouts with PicassoIV using the Prefs- or TurboPrint
   driver are only possible with the version 1.23 of Picasso96 
   (rtg.library V40.2589)or above.
   The problem was the rtg.library.

   I noticed the same problems with Pagestream.


@{fg shine}Solution by Manni Froitzheim - 08-02-97:@{fg text}
   I had a lot of troubles with the Picasso IV too the way that FW only
   prints a lot of color waste.
   The customer support of Village Tronic is really the worst. I've no
   reply of them for 2 weeks now!

   Well, a friend of mine got a version of the P96 software from somewhere
   (Aminet or how knows...). With this version everything works okay and
   FW prints without any problem.

   This version is called InstallPicasso96 with the date 5-14-97.

   I also have some @{"wishes" link "wunsch18"} for FW.


@{fg shine}Solution by Andreas Peter - 07-27-97:@{fg text}
   I've got equal problems compared to them of Arndt. While printing
   there were additional carriage returns in equal intervals.

   I use an Epson Stylus Color printer.

   Now I've tried the solution by Siegfried and Markus. But there was
   no change. 
   After that I've installed Turboprint @{fg shine}4.1@{fg text} and,
   guess what, it works. The printout looks finally normal.
   With a Workbench driver from the Aminet the error hasn't occurred,
   this means it seems not to be a memory conflict between Picasso96 and
   FW.
   I think the problem is TurboPrint 5.0!


@{fg shine}Solution by Markus Steblei - 06-28-97:@{fg text}
   The problem concerning Picasso96 and FW is already known and a fix
   is in work: The Picasso96 driver seems to cause a memory conflict
   with the printing routine of FW.
   Here is a Tip by Oberland Computer for printing texts:
   Start using a boot disk without the P96 driver (now you need a flickerfixer  
   or a monitor that can handle PAL or NTSC). Now you can print as usual.
   The programmers of P96 are just working on a patch. (Maybe Softwood should
   improve the printing routine of FW and fix the bug the same time.)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage016" "Question from Arndt Bußmann"

@{fg shine}Problem and Solution:@{fg text}
   I've programmed a small workaround with ARexx. This script takes care 
   that FW prints out all the pages into PostScript files and sends them
   afterwards to the HWGPostscript interpreter which prints them correctly.
   It's interesting that this method is much faster for printing in the 
   landscape format than FW itself. (FW is using the lame ChipRam for printing
   anyway). Even large PostScript graphics are printed without any rendering
   error or lost pixels.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage017" "Question by Arndt Bußmann"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   Some time ago the ARexx port of FW was really good working but now FW crashes
   (Guru : 80..04 ILLEGAL INSTRUCTION) at least when using the following two
   commands: CurrentObject and Status fontsize.
   (But who knows maybe this is only a problem of my computer?).

@{fg shine}Solution by Arndt himself:@{fg text}
   After deleting the old libraries of FW5 in LIBS: everything was okay.
   That's because the update only replaces the files in FWLibs.
   When FW starts it first looks in the LIBS: drawer. FW97 then uses the
   old  FW5 libraries.
   Regards to all the Amiga fans, Arndt

   Editor's note: 
   You should always delete all FW specific libraries out of LIBS: and only
   use those in the FWLibs directory. With that you can be sure that after an
   update only the latest libraries are used.


@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   FinalWriter overwrites only libraries in the FWLibs directory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage018" "Question by Thomas Prokop -  09-08-96"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   Is there any solution to use MagicMenu together with FW meanwhile?

@{fg shine}Solution by letter from unknown - 08-16-97:@{fg text}
   To use FW (Ger V5.05) together with MagicMenu (V1.29) you have to
   replace the latest version of "swshell.library" with an older one.
   FW & MagicMenu are working together without any problem using the
   "swshell.library" V7.4 on OS3.0 and e.g. GVP 030. With the latest
   version 8.6 it isn't possible.

               (Sender is unknown; either address nor signature)

@{fg shine}Note by me - 01-07-97:@{fg text}
   Meanwhile the official version 2.15 is available at the Aminet.
   "Aminet:util/cdity/MagicMenu_2_15.lha"

@{fg shine}Note by Thomas Raukamp - 12-13-96:@{fg text}
   On my computer FW3 runs together with MagiMenu  (Version 1.6
   as well as the latest version 2.0ß) without any
   problems (I don't know if this works with all versions).
   
@{fg shine}Note by Christian Beck - 12-07-96:@{fg text}
   Source: http://fsinfo.cs.uni-sb.de/~cattaneo/magicmenu/magicmenu.html
   (at the moment there is available Version 2.0, revision 2.14)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage019" "Question by Christian Beck - 03-02-97"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}

   Why isn't it possible to select "bold" or "italic" if the 
   Postscript fonts (.pfb) have normal names?

@{fg shine}Solution by Christian Beck - 03-02-97:@{fg text}

   When choosing "bold", "italic" or something, FinalWriter searches
   for the font that ends with "_bold", "_italic" and so on.

@{fg shine}Note by Heiko Schröder - 12-12-97:@{fg text}
   There's an easy way to solve this problem. Rename the various 
   font styles of a font:

   LatienneSwaT-@{fg fill}Regu@{fg text}.pfb        |          LatienneSwaT
   LatienneSwaT-@{fg fill}ReguItal@{fg text}.pfb    |_____>    LatienneSwaT@{fg fill}_Italic@{fg text}
   LatienneSwaT-@{fg fill}Bold@{fg text}.pfb        |     >    LatienneSwaT@{fg fill}_Bold@{fg text}
   LatienneSwaT-@{fg fill}BoldItal@{fg text}.pfb    |          LatienneSwaT@{fg fill}_BoldItalic@{fg text}

   Now FW automatically recognizes the different styles and loads them. 

@{fg fill}Update: @{fg text}Notice the following style names:

            Book            |
            Light           |---->   normal (no extension)
            Medium          |
            Regular         |
            Roman           |
            Thin            |
            UltraLight      |

       (...)Italic          |---->   italic (_italic)
       (...)Oblique         |

           (Ultra)Black     |
           (Extra)Bold      |
            Compact         |
            Demi            |---->   bold   (_bold)
            Heavy           |
            Poster          |
            Semi(Bold)      |
            Ultra           |


           (Ultra)Condensed |
            Narrow          |---->   don't fit in the list
            Extend          |

      Taken from: Turtschi, Ralf: "Praktische Typographie", Niggli AG,
                  CH-Sulgen - ISBN 3-7212-0292-9

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage020" "Question by Andreas Peter - 04-14-97"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   For my business I often have to create texts containing drawings,
   and so I would like to export the documents to RTF!
   The texts have been saved almost correct but not the graphics!!!
   Is it possible with the graphics at least?

@{fg shine}Answer:@{fg text}
   Now I have to say NO, sorry.
   RTF (Rich Text Format) only saves text formats right with the appropriate
   font and styles (bold, italic...).
   So graphics were not planned for this.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   Only a few PC programs (e.g. WinWord) offer the possibility to include
   graphics into RTF documents. The graphics data is then "uuencoded".

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Frage021" "Question by Michael Krüger - 05-02-97"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   Sometimes hyphenation is out of control. It happens especially with 
   Type-1 fonts with kerning that often changes. The problem is that FW
   hyphenates/divides a word but if you are going on typing it still hyphenates
   the word and sends more and more character to the previous line.
   Finally the whole word stands on this line (ignoring the right indent).
   Saying "Good bye" to the justified text alignment, or what?

@{fg shine}Answer by Christian Beck - 06-14-97@{fg text}
   I still own Version 5.05 and I've got the same problems with it. 
   But you can solve them easy as this:
   Every time FinalWriter makes some trouble just press "Hyphenation off & on"
   on the toolbar. Now FinalWriter calculates again and everything is okay.
   You get the same result with reloading the document.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage022" "Qustion by Dieter Brumberg - 08-22-96"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}   
   Because of my business I often need signs like "m˛, mł", but also the
   root sign. I would prefer to get both the characters as one unit.
   Therefor you may need a paint program for letters/characters I think.
   Do you have experiences with this and what software do you use?

@{fg shine}Solution No. 1 by Christian Beck - 01-21-97:@{fg text}
   Amiga OS can manage 2 or more characters by using the standard keyboard
   definition. There are some good programs to change these definitions
   (e.g. EditKey by David Kinder).

-December 96-
   There was published a program for creating mathematical expressions. 
   You can find it at the Aminet »misc/math/MathScript32.lha«. 
   It's also available at some Aminet-CDs.
   »MathScript« is shareware. This means you get 21 days to evaluate the
   program. After that you should pay the author 30,- DM.

                          Simon Ihmig
                          Beim Rauhen Hause 30
                          D-22111 Hamburg
                          Germany

                          Fax:   +49 (0)40 65901168
                          EMail: Ihmig@tu-harburg.d400.de

   The program allows you to create expressions in the IFF format and (maybe much
   more important) exports them into EPS files.
   It also exists an ARexx port. The package includes ARexx macros for use with
   FinalWriter to instantly load the expressions into a document.


@{fg shine}Solution No. 2:@{fg text}

   -August 96-
   There is a freeware program called @{b}MathPaint@{ub} by Urs Fleisch.
   That's his address:
				Urs Fleisch
                        Leimatstr. 38
                        CH-9000 St.Gallen

   This program allows you to easily edit mathematical expressions.
   It also supports math signs like integral, sum, operators, scalar
   multiplication, Greek letters, root. 
   After creating your expression, you can save it as an IFF file
   and load it as graphics into @{b}Finalwriter@{ub}.
   Because the IFF graphics is a normal bitmap the printout will be
   of less quality unfortunately.
   But because I don't see any other possibility, I think you can
   live with that.

@{fg shine}Description:@{fg text}
   Unfortunately the team of Softwood once again forgot to include 
   a function for creating mathematical signs and expressions.
   They probably want to keep it for another update.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage023" "Question by Dirk Neubauer"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}

   A quite curious thing was happen to me as I used the
   FinalWriter last time.
   I was writing a letter just as usual. Then I've used the spell
   checker. After that I found some text phrases that need to
   be changed. But at this point the machine always crashed
   at one single character. I've tried to type the word
   "Photogrammetrie". I could write it in every other paragraph and
   I could also write any other word at this part of the paragraph.
   Only this single word is not accepted and nothing goes after I've typed
   the "i" of it.
   I wrote the word somewhere else cut it and tried to paste it into the
   correct paragraph -> system crash! 
   I saved the text in ASCII format, inserted the missing word "Photogrammetrie"
   and loaded it again into FW -> system crash.
   Finally I wrote the letter using Wordworth. I own the SE version.

   Where's the problem? Was the paragraph to large? But I could insert anything
   other at this place. I really don't know - it's a mystery to me.

@{fg shine}Solution by Siegfried Sulovsky - :@{fg text}

   Unfortunately Dirk writes nothing about his configuration and version of FW.
   I could not repeat the situation with FW97. To clear up the question I would
   use SnoopDOS 3.0. Just to see where the problem is exactly.

   Excerpt AmigaPlus 6/97 Workshop for SnoopDOS 3.0:

   -------------------------------------------------------------------------
   System Crash:

   If the program crashes while you are logging, set SnoopDOS to trace mode
   (step by step program execution). At this mode it waits before it executes
   the next function call until you click at "Project/Single Step" again.
   This gives you the possibility to inspect the effect of every single 
   function call. Now you can check what cases the system crash.

   -------------------------------------------------------------------------

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage024" "Tip by Andreas Volkmann"

@{fg shine}Problem:@{fg text}
   The only problem I've got occurred if I tried to move text into
   my manual without changing graphics. The clock appeared and nothing
   was happening any longer. After around 1 hour I made a reset because
   I didn't felt like waiting another long time.

@{fg shine}Solution:@{fg text}
   I solved the problem by changing the way of working 
   (first writing the new text, then deleting the old text with 
   backspaces and afterwards checking the style of the following text).
 
   At this time I've used the following configuration:   
   A4000/040/25Mhz 18Mb Ram   size of the text file 900 KB (graphics included)
   Meanwhile I own some better stuff but I could not notice changes concerning the
   problem because I have no time to continue my work.
   At the moment FinalWriter97 runs without any problems on my 4000 with this
   configuration: A4000/040/40Mhz 34Mb Ram PicassoIV with 800x600 in 64k

   See you
   Andreas

@ENDNODE

@NODE "frage025" "Tip by Christian Beck - 07-11-97"

      I've never got problems printing with my Laserjet 5L (except that it's
